When it comes to healthier it's not that clear. Dietary cholesterol for most people has small impact on cholesterol levels in blood. Your body produces way more. And it depends on activity levels among other things. Also I'm not sure about it but i seem to recall that the impossible burger has more carbohydrates. With diabetes being a population level issue. I wouldn't go as far as claiming that they are healthier without any direct studies done.
As for ecological impact just as Bill said most of that animal impact is beef. So if you replace beef patties with plant based there is a big impact. When replacing pork it still benefits but to a lesser extent. Still... that is the most convincing argument for them.
I'd love to try those myself but in Poland they are really hard to get.

snippet.textDisplay: Cow farts/burps are a non-issue. Yeah, they release greenhouse gasses, but the carbon is coming from the plants they eat, which will be regrown the next year. So that carbon is in a stable cycle: plant -> cow -> fart -> plant -> cow -> fart -> etc. The bigger problem is destroying carbon sinks (such as rainforest) and converting to livestock area. Livestock area has very few carbon sinks other than the cows' bodies).

snippet.textDisplay: I tried some of these burgers. Impossible burgers taste close enough to meat and very delicious, better than the old veggie burgers I’ve tasted years ago. I’m not a vegetarian or vegan, but I’m open to trying out a lot of vegan alternatives that taste better than they look. Anyways, the only meat stuff I eat are chicken, turkey, beef, lamb, deer, whatever else are Kosher and Halal. I don’t eat pork, or seafood (shrimps, crabs, squids, lobsters), maybe except fish with fins and scales, but that’s occasionally. Religion aside, but there’s scientific reasons why I don’t eat pork.
